{# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
   /heatmap — standalone carve-out of the BvSM §2b heatmap.

   The strategic thesis: the heatmap is the empirical bottom line of the
   BvSM article. As a standalone page it serves a different job from the
   article — it's the hook, the shareable artifact, the thing a curious
   visitor lands on and engages with before they're committed to reading
   3,000 words of prose. The page should let the viz do the work, then
   funnel engaged visitors back into the full argument.

   Architecture: this page reuses the BvSM heatmap component verbatim
   (same markup, same CSS, same JS). The only new ingredients are the
   hero framing, the CTA section, and a small JS extension to
   jumpToCalc() that detects standalone context and navigates to the
   BvSM page with the clicked-cell's parameters as a URL query string.
   The BvSM page's init reads those params and applies them to its §2
   calculator on load — closing the loop.

   Editorial framing: deliberately minimal. Hero gets the reader oriented
   in 3 sentences. The viz is the page. The CTA at the bottom is the
   primary outbound link.
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

<main class="heatmap-standalone">

    <section class="heatmap-hero">
        <h1>The <em>Bitcoin</em> Heatmap</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">
            Every monthly entry since 2010, every common holding horizon &mdash; bitcoin's outperformance against the S&amp;P 500 and the NASDAQ-100 across roughly 1,500 possible windows, in one grid.
        </p>
        <p class="heatmap-howto">
            Amber means bitcoin won; red means it lost; intensity shows by how much. <strong>Click any cell to load that exact entry into the full calculator.</strong>
        </p>
    </section>

    {# ═══ HEATMAP — markup mirrors bvsm.njk §2b verbatim ═══════════
       Wrapped in .bvsm-page to satisfy a handful of descendant
       selectors in bvsm.css that scope to that ancestor. The IDs
       match BvSM exactly; bvsm.js's initHeatmap() guards on
       #bvsmHeatmapGrid presence and will pick this up identically.
       The §1/§2/§3 modules in bvsm.js no-op cleanly here because
       their target IDs don't exist on this page.

       One editorial deviation from BvSM: the legend note. On the
       article page it says "load that start date in the calculator
       above" because the §2 calc is literally above the heatmap.
       Here there IS no calc above — the click navigates to the
       full BvSM page — so the note reflects that destination.
       ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
    <div class="bvsm-page">
        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-wrapper">
            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-controls">
                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-control-group">
                    <span class="bvsm-heatmap-control-label">Bitcoin compared to:</span>
                    <button class="bvsm-heatmap-cmp-btn is-active" data-hm-cmp="sp500" type="button">S&amp;P 500 TR</button>
                    <button class="bvsm-heatmap-cmp-btn"           data-hm-cmp="ndq"   type="button">NASDAQ-100 TR</button>
                </div>
                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-control-group">
                    <span class="bvsm-heatmap-control-label">Bitcoin mode:</span>
                    <button class="bvsm-heatmap-mode-btn is-active" data-hm-mode="lump" type="button">Lump-sum</button>
                    <button class="bvsm-heatmap-mode-btn"           data-hm-mode="dca"  type="button">Weekly DCA</button>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-layout">
                <div class="bvsm-heatmap-main">
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-scroll-container" id="bvsmHeatmapScroll">
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-yaxis" id="bvsmHeatmapYaxis"></div>
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-gridwrap">
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-grid" id="bvsmHeatmapGrid"></div>
                            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-xaxis" id="bvsmHeatmapXaxis"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend">
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-scale">
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="loss-deep">&lt;&#x2212;50%</span>
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="loss">&#x2212;50% &mdash; &#x2212;10%</span>
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="flat">&#x00B1;10%</span>
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-mild">+10% &mdash; 2&times;</span>
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-mid">2&times; &mdash; 5&times;</span>
                            <span class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-cell" data-tier="win-deep">&gt;5&times;</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="bvsm-heatmap-legend-note">Color = bitcoin&rsquo;s outperformance multiple over the comparator. Click any cell to explore that start date in the full calculator.</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <aside class="bvsm-heatmap-sidebar" id="bvsmHeatmapSidebar" aria-label="Pattern summary"></aside>
            </div>

            <div class="bvsm-heatmap-tooltip" id="bvsmHeatmapTooltip" role="tooltip" aria-hidden="true"></div>
        </div>
    </div>

    {# ═══ CTA — the page's primary outbound link ═══════════════════
       This is the hook-to-article conversion point. Visitors who
       engaged with the heatmap (clicked a cell, scrolled the
       horizons, toggled comparator) are warm leads for the full
       argument. Make this prominent and the link unambiguous.
       ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
    <section class="heatmap-cta">
        <div class="heatmap-cta-inner">
            <div class="heatmap-cta-label">See the full argument</div>
            <h2 class="heatmap-cta-title">Bitcoin vs. The Stock Market</h2>
            <p>This grid is the empirical bottom line of a longer analysis. The full page builds the case from the start &mdash; the Power Law framework that anticipated the pattern, individual cyclical-top stress tests against the worst possible entries, and the forward projection across a typical investor's holding horizon.</p>
            <a href="/bitcoin-vs-the-stock-market.html" class="heatmap-cta-button">Read &laquo;Bitcoin vs. The Stock Market&raquo; &rarr;</a>
        </div>
    </section>

</main>
